    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Payables Overview",
            Slug = "payables-overview",
            Summary = "What Accounts Payable covers: vendor bills, vendor payments, the bill lifecycle, payment application, and how payables connect to Purchase Orders and Vendors.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/payables"]""",
            Tags = """["payables","ap","accounting"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Payables Overview\n\nThe Payables module is your Accounts Payable (AP) workspace. It tracks the money your shop owes vendors: the **vendor bills** you receive, the **vendor payments** you make to settle them, and the way those payments are applied against open balances. Payables connects directly to Purchase Orders (for matched billing) and to Vendors (every bill and payment belongs to one vendor).\n\nThe page is organized into tabs — **Bills**, **Payments**, **Batches**, and **Accounts** — with a vendor filter and a status filter at the top to narrow what you see.\n\n### What Is a Vendor Bill?\n\nA vendor bill represents an invoice you owe a vendor. Each bill has:\n- A unique **Bill Number** (auto-generated)\n- A link to exactly one **Vendor**\n- An optional **Vendor Invoice #** (the vendor's own reference)\n- A **Bill Date** and a **Due Date**\n- One or more **Line Items** (description, quantity, unit price)\n- An optional **Tax Amount**\n- A **Status** that drives where the bill is in its lifecycle\n- Computed totals: **Total**, **Paid** (amount paid), and **Balance Due**\n\nBills can be entered two ways. A **standalone** bill is typed in by hand — you add free-form line items. A **From Purchase Order** bill is matched to a PO: you pick the PO and bill against its received lines, and you can only bill up to the quantity that has been received but not yet billed (three-way matching).\n\n### Bill Lifecycle\n\nVendor bills move through these statuses:\n\n1. **Draft** — The bill has been entered but not yet approved. It has no general-ledger impact yet. This is the initial status for every new bill.\n2. **Approved** — The bill has been approved for payment. The AP journal posts on this transition. Approve a bill from the detail panel using the **Approve Bill** button (available only from Draft).\n3. **Partially Paid** — The bill is approved and one or more vendor payments have settled part of the balance. Balance Due is still greater than zero.\n4. **Paid** — The bill is fully settled. Balance Due is zero.\n5. **Void** — The bill was cancelled before it was paid. A bill can be voided only from Draft or Approved status, only when nothing has been paid against it, and only when it did not originate from an expense.\n\n### What Is a Vendor Payment?\n\nA vendor payment records money sent to a vendor and how it is applied to that vendor's open bills. Each payment has:\n- A unique **Payment #** (auto-generated)\n- A **Vendor**\n- A **Method** (Cash, Check, Credit Card, Bank Transfer, Wire, or Other)\n- An **Amount**\n- A **Payment Date**\n- An optional **Reference #** (check number, wire reference, etc.)\n- One or more **Bill Applications** that spread the payment across open bills\n\nWhen you create a payment, you choose a vendor and the system loads that vendor's payable bills (those in Approved or Partially Paid status). You enter how much of the payment to apply to each bill. The sum of applications may not exceed the payment amount; anything left over shows as **Unapplied**. Applying a payment moves each affected bill toward Partially Paid or Paid automatically.\n\n### Payment Transmission (Electronic Payments)\n\nElectronic payments — Bank Transfer and Wire — carry a **Transmission Status** that tracks the bank handoff: Queued, Retrying, Succeeded, Failed, or Cancelled. A failed transmission surfaces a banner at the top of the page and on the bill and payment detail. You can **Retry Transmission** on a failed payment. Wire payments add a dual-control step: while a wire is Queued you must **Attest Wire** (a second user confirms it) before it transmits.\n\n### How Payables Connects to Other Features\n\n**Purchase Orders:** A bill created From Purchase Order is matched line-by-line to the PO's received quantities. You can only bill received-but-unbilled quantity, and price differences flow through as purchase-price variance when the bill posts.\n\n**Vendors:** Every bill and payment belongs to one vendor. The vendor name links to the vendor record, and the vendor filter at the top of the page scopes both the Bills and Payments tabs.\n\n**Expenses:** A vendor-settled expense can be promoted into a vendor bill automatically. Such a bill shows a 'From Expense' chip and cannot be voided.\n\n**Accounting boundary:** Payables is an accounting feature. When an external accounting provider is connected, AP is managed there instead; the built-in AP module runs in standalone mode.\n\n### Bank Accounts and NACHA Payment Batches (Optional)\n\nWhen your shop is set up to originate its own ACH payments, two extra tabs appear on the Payables page: **Accounts** and **Batches**. These are gated by the **CAP-BANK-NACHA** capability and are hidden until an administrator enables it (after the bank's ACH-origination agreement is in place). Only Admin, Manager, and Office Manager roles can use them.\n\n- The **Accounts** tab holds each vendor's bank account (routing and account numbers). Numbers are encrypted at rest and shown masked; adding or changing them requires a second user to approve (dual control) and a zero-dollar prenote to verify the account before it can be paid. See the dedicated 'Vendor Bank Accounts & Dual Control' module.\n- The **Batches** tab assembles approved Bank Transfer payments into a NACHA file you download and upload to your bank portal, then a second user releases the batch (segregation of duties). It also imports the bank's ACH return / NOC file. See the dedicated 'NACHA Payment Batches' module.\n\nIf you do not see these tabs, your install pays vendors by check, wire, or another method and does not originate ACH files from Forge — that is normal.\n\n### When to Use Payables\n\n- When a vendor invoice arrives — enter it as a bill, then approve it for payment\n- When you want three-way matching — create the bill From Purchase Order so billing is bounded by received quantity\n- When you pay a vendor — record a payment and apply it across that vendor's open bills\n- When an electronic payment fails — retry the transmission from the payment detail\n- When you need a wire approved — attest the queued wire before it sends","sections":[]}"""
        });

